[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] Diesel is an ORM and query builder designed to reduce the boilerplate for database interactions.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] If this is your first time reading this documentation, we recommend you start with the getting started guide.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] We also have many other long form guides.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] For Diesel to validate your queries at compile time it requires you to specify your schema in your code, which you can do with the `table!` macro.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] `diesel print-schema` can be used to automatically generate these macro calls (by connecting to your database and querying its schema).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] Queries usually start from either a table, or a function like `update`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] Diesel provides a `prelude` module, which exports most of the typically used traits and types.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] We are conservative about what goes in this module, and avoid anything which has a generic name.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] Files which use Diesel are expected to have `use diesel::prelude::*;`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] Types which represent the result of a SQL query implement a trait called `Queryable`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] You can find all the types supported by Diesel in the `sql_types` module.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] These types are only used to represent a SQL type.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] You should never put them on your `Queryable` structs.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] To find all the Rust types which can be used with a given SQL type, see the documentation for that SQL type.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] To find all the SQL types which can be used with a Rust type, go to the docs for either `ToSql` or `FromSql`, go to the “Implementors” section, and find the Rust type you want to use.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] Diesel is known for generating large complicated looking errors.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] Usually most of these error messages can be broken down easily.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] The following section tries to give an overview of common error messages and how to read them.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] As a general note it’s always useful to read the complete error message as emitted by rustc, including the `required because of …` part of the message.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/latest-diesel] If you run into problems, Diesel has an active community.
