[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] In database management systems (DBMS), a **prepared statement**, **parameterized statement**, (not to be confused with **parameterized query**) is a feature where the database pre-compiles SQL code and stores the results, separating it from data.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] A prepared statement takes the form of a pre-compiled template into which constant values are substituted during each execution, and typically use SQL DML statements such as INSERT, SELECT, or UPDATE.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] **Compile**: The DBMS compiles (parses, optimizes and translates) the statement template, and stores the result without executing it.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] **Execute**: The application supplies (or *binds*) values for the parameters of the statement template, and the DBMS executes the statement (possibly returning a result).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] The application may request the DBMS to execute the statement many times with different values.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] In the above example, the application might supply the values "bike" for the first parameter and "10900" for the second parameter, and then later the values "shoes" and "7400".
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] The alternative to a prepared statement is calling SQL directly from the application source code in a way that combines code and data.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] Not all optimization can be performed at the time the statement template is compiled, for two reasons: the best plan may depend on the specific values of the parameters, and the best plan may change as tables and indexes change over time.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] On the other hand, if a query is executed only once, server-side prepared statements can be slower because of the additional round-trip to the server.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] Implementation limitations may also lead to performance penalties; for example, some versions of MySQL did not cache results of prepared queries.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] A stored procedure, which is also precompiled and stored on the server for later execution, has similar advantages.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] Unlike a stored procedure, a prepared statement is not normally written in a procedural language and cannot use or modify variables or use control flow structures, relying instead on the declarative database query language.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] Due to their simplicity and client-side emulation, prepared statements are more portable across vendors.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] Major DBMSs, including SQLite, MySQL, Oracle, IBM Db2, Microsoft SQL Server and PostgreSQL support prepared statements.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] Prepared statements are normally executed through a non-SQL binary protocol for efficiency and protection from SQL injection, but with some DBMSs such as MySQL prepared statements are also available using a SQL syntax for debugging purposes.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] A number of programming languages support prepared statements in their standard libraries and will emulate them on the client side even if the underlying DBMS does not support them, including Java's JDBC, Perl's DBI, PHP's PDO and Python's DB-API.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] Client-side emulation can be faster for queries which are executed only once, by reducing the number of round trips to the server, but is usually slower for queries executed many times.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] It resists SQL injection attacks equally effectively.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] Many types of SQL injection attacks can be eliminated by *disabling literals*, effectively requiring the use of prepared statements; as of 2007 only H2 supports this feature.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] In C++ MySQL Connector/C++ X DevAPI, preparation is done implicitly using the library's API.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] ADO.NET `SqlCommand` will accept any type for the `value` parameter of `AddWithValue`, and type conversion occurs automatically.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] Note the use of "named parameters" (i.e.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] `"@username"`) rather than `"?"`—this allows you to use a parameter multiple times and in any arbitrary order within the query command text.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] However, the AddWithValue method should not be used with variable length data types, like varchar and nvarchar.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] This is because .NET assumes the length of the parameter to be the length of the given value, rather than getting the actual length from the database via reflection.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] The consequence of this is that a different query plan is compiled and stored for each different length.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] In general, the maximum number of "duplicate" plans is the product of the lengths of the variable length columns as specified in the database.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] `command.Parameters.Add(ParamName, VarChar, ParamLength).Value = ParamValue`, where ParamLength is the length as specified in the database.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] Since the standard Add method needs to be used for variable length data types, it is a good habit to use it for all parameter types.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] The placeholder parameter syntax differs depending on your database.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] MySQL, SQL Server and SQLite use the ? notation, but PostgreSQL uses the $N notation.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/prepared-statement] Java `PreparedStatement` provides "setters" (`setInt(int), setString(String), setDouble(double),` etc.) for all major built-in data types.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/query-language] A **query language**, also known as **data query language** or **database query language** (**DQL**), is a computer language used to make queries in databases and information systems.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/query-language] In database systems, query languages rely on strict theory to retrieve information.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/query-language] A well known example is the Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/query-language] Broadly, query languages can be classified according to whether they are *database* query languages or *information retrieval* query languages.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/query-language] The difference is that a **database query language** attempts to give factual answers to factual questions, while an **information retrieval query language** attempts to find documents containing information that is relevant to an area of inquiry.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/relational-database] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] In computer science, **type safety** is the extent to which a programming language discourages or prevents type errors.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Type-safe languages are sometimes also called **strongly** or **strictly typed**.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] The behaviors classified as type errors by a given programming language are usually those that result from attempts to perform operations on values that are not of the appropriate data type, e.g. trying to add a string to an integer.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Type enforcement can be static (catching potential errors at compile time), dynamic (associating type information with values at run-time and consulting them as needed to detect imminent errors), or a combination of both.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Dynamic type enforcement can often run programs that would be invalid under static enforcement, but at the cost of introducing errors at runtime.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] In the context of static (compile-time) type systems, type safety usually involves (among other things) a guarantee that the eventual value of any expression will be a legitimate member of that expression's static type.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] The precise requirement is more subtle than this — see, for example, subtyping and polymorphism for complications.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] In other words, if a type system is *sound*, then expressions accepted by that type system must evaluate to a value of the appropriate type (rather than produce a value of some other, unrelated type or crash with a type error).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] A language is type-safe if the only operations that can be performed on data in the language are those sanctioned by the type of the data.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] However, what precisely it means for a program to be "well typed" or to "go wrong" are properties of its static and dynamic semantics, which are specific to each programming language.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Consequently, a precise, formal definition of type soundness depends upon the style of formal semantics used to specify a language.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] In 1994, Andrew Wright and Matthias Felleisen formulated what has become the standard definition and proof technique for type safety in languages defined by operational semantics, which is closest to the notion of type safety as understood by most programmers.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] or can be reduced towards a value in some well-defined way.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] In other words, the program never gets into an undefined state where no further transitions are possible.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] A number of other formal treatments of type soundness have also been published in terms of denotational semantics and structural operational semantics.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] In isolation, type soundness is a relatively weak property, as it essentially just states that the rules of a type system are internally consistent and cannot be subverted.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Type safety is usually a requirement for any toy language (i.e., esoteric language) proposed in academic programming language research.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] However, many languages are too big for human-generated type safety proofs, as they often require checking thousands of cases.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Nevertheless, some languages such as Standard ML, which has rigorously defined semantics, have been proved to meet one definition of type safety.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Regardless of the properties of the language definition, certain errors may occur at run-time due to bugs in the implementation, or in linked libraries written in other languages; such errors could render a given implementation type unsafe in certain circumstances.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] An early version of Sun's Java virtual machine was vulnerable to this sort of problem.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Programming languages are often colloquially classified as strongly typed or weakly typed (also loosely typed) to refer to certain aspects of type safety.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Type safety is closely linked to memory safety.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Conversely, if the language is memory-safe, it cannot allow an arbitrary integer to be used as a pointer, hence there must be a separate pointer or reference type.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] As a minimal condition, a type-safe language must not allow dangling pointers across allocations of different types.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] But most languages enforce the proper use of abstract data types defined by programmers even when this is not strictly necessary for memory safety or for the prevention of any kind of catastrophic failure.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Allocations are given a type describing its contents, and this type is fixed for the duration of the allocation.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] This allows type-based alias analysis to infer that allocations of different types are distinct.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Most type-safe languages use garbage collection.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Pierce says, "it is extremely difficult to achieve type safety in the presence of an explicit deallocation operation", due to the dangling pointer problem.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] However Rust is generally considered type-safe and uses a borrow checker to achieve memory safety, instead of garbage collection.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] In object-oriented languages type safety is usually intrinsic in the fact that a type system is in place.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] This is expressed in terms of class definitions.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] A class essentially defines the structure of the objects derived from it and an API as a *contract* for handling these objects.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Each time a new object is created it will *comply* with that contract.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Each function that exchanges objects derived from a specific class, or implementing a specific interface, will adhere to that contract: hence in that function the operations permitted on that object will be only those defined by the methods of the class the object implements.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] This will guarantee that the object integrity will be preserved.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Exceptions to this are object oriented languages that allow dynamic modification of the object structure, or the use of reflection to modify the content of an object to overcome the constraints imposed by the class methods definitions.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Ada was designed to be suitable for embedded systems, device drivers and other forms of system programming, but also to encourage type-safe programming.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] To resolve these conflicting goals, Ada confines type-unsafety to a certain set of special constructs whose names usually begin with the string Unchecked_.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Unchecked_Deallocation can be effectively banned from a unit of Ada text by applying pragma Pure to this unit.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] It is expected that programmers will use Unchecked_ constructs very carefully and only when necessary; programs that do not use them are type-safe.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] The SPARK programming language is a subset of Ada eliminating all its potential ambiguities and insecurities while at the same time adding statically checked contracts to the language features available.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] SPARK avoids the issues with dangling pointers by disallowing allocation at run time entirely.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Ada2012 adds statically checked contracts to the language itself (in form of pre-, and post-conditions, as well as type invariants).
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] The C programming language is type-safe in limited contexts; for example, a compile-time error is generated when an attempt is made to convert a pointer to one type of structure to a pointer to another type of structure, unless an explicit cast is used.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] However, a number of very common operations are non-type-safe; for example, the usual way to print an integer is something like `printf("%d", 12)`, where the `%d` tells `printf` at run-time to expect an integer argument.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] In addition, C, like Ada, provides unspecified or undefined explicit conversions; and unlike in Ada, idioms that use these conversions are very common, and have helped to give C a type-unsafe reputation.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] For example, the standard way to allocate memory on the heap is to invoke a memory allocation function, such as `malloc`, with an argument indicating how many bytes are required.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] The function returns a void pointer (`void*`), which the calling code must explicitly or implicitly cast to the appropriate pointer type.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Pre-standardized implementations of C required an explicit cast to do so, therefore for an allocation of some `struct Foo`, the code `Foo* foo = (struct Foo*)malloc(sizeof(struct Foo))` became the accepted practice.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] `malloc()` returns `void*` which does not need to be explicitly cast in C, but in C++ this casting is made mandatory for type safety.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] It has support for untyped pointers, but this must be accessed using the "unsafe" keyword which can be prohibited at the compiler level.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] It has inherent support for run-time cast validation.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Casts can be validated by using the "as" keyword that will return a null reference if the cast is invalid, or by using a C-style cast that will throw an exception if the cast is invalid.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Undue reliance on the object type (from which all other types are derived) runs the risk of defeating the purpose of the C# type system.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] It is usually better practice to abandon object references in favour of generics, similar to templates in C++ and generics in Java.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] The Java language is designed to enforce type safety.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Anything in Java *happens* inside an object and each object is an instance of a class.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] To implement the *type safety* enforcement, each object, before usage, needs to be allocated.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Java allows usage of primitive types but only inside properly allocated objects.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Sometimes a part of the type safety is implemented indirectly: e.g. the class BigDecimal represents a floating point number of arbitrary precision, but handles only numbers that can be expressed with a finite representation.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] The operation BigDecimal.divide() calculates a new object as the division of two numbers expressed as BigDecimal.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] In this case if the division has no finite representation, as when one computes e.g.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] 1/3=0.33333..., the divide() method can raise an exception if no rounding mode is defined for the operation.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Hence the library, rather than the language, guarantees that the object respects the contract implicit in the class definition.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Standard ML has rigorously defined semantics and is known to be type-safe.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] However, some implementations, including Standard ML of New Jersey (SML/NJ), its syntactic variant Mythryl and MLton, provide libraries that offer unsafe operations.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] These facilities are often used in conjunction with those implementations' foreign function interfaces to interact with non-ML code (such as C libraries) that may require data laid out in specific ways.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Another example is the SML/NJ interactive toplevel itself, which must use unsafe operations to execute ML code entered by the user.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Modula-2 is a strongly-typed language with a design philosophy to require any unsafe facilities to be explicitly marked as unsafe.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] This is achieved by "moving" such facilities into a built-in pseudo-library called SYSTEM from where they must be imported before they can be used.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] The import thus makes it visible when such facilities are used.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Unfortunately, this was not consequently implemented in the original language report and its implementation.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] There still remained unsafe facilities such as the type cast syntax and variant records (inherited from Pascal) that could be used without prior import.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] The difficulty in moving these facilities into the SYSTEM pseudo-module was the lack of any identifier for the facility that could then be imported since only identifiers can be imported, but not syntax.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] The ISO Modula-2 standard corrected this for the type cast facility by changing the type cast syntax into a function called CAST which has to be imported from pseudo-module SYSTEM.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] However, other unsafe facilities such as variant records remained available without any import from pseudo-module SYSTEM.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] A recent revision of the language applied the original design philosophy rigorously.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] First, pseudo-module SYSTEM was renamed to UNSAFE to make the unsafe nature of facilities imported from there more explicit.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Then all remaining unsafe facilities where either removed altogether (for example variant records) or moved to pseudo-module UNSAFE.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] For facilities where there is no identifier that could be imported, enabling identifiers were introduced.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] In order to enable such a facility, its corresponding enabling identifier must be imported from pseudo-module UNSAFE.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] No unsafe facilities remain in the language that do not require import from UNSAFE.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Pascal has had a number of type safety requirements, some of which are kept in some compilers.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Where a Pascal compiler dictates "strict typing", two variables cannot be assigned to each other unless they are either compatible (such as conversion of integer to real) or assigned to the identical subtype.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] Under strict typing, a variable defined as TwoTypes is *not compatible* with DualTypes (because they are not identical, even though the components of that user defined type are identical) and an assignment of `T1 := D2;` is illegal.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] An assignment of `T1 := T2;` would be legal because the subtypes they are defined to *are* identical.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] However, an assignment such as `T1.Q := D1.Q;` would be legal.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] In general, Common Lisp is a type-safe language.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] A Common Lisp compiler is responsible for inserting dynamic checks for operations whose type safety cannot be proven statically.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] However, a programmer may indicate that a program should be compiled with a lower level of dynamic type-checking.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] A program compiled in such a mode cannot be considered type-safe.
[src:diesel-orm-rust/type-safety] The following examples illustrates how C++ cast operators can break type safety when used incorrectly.
